# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
- Since we are talking about a grid, we might need a nested loop to solve the problem.
- One way to solve this problem would be iterating over a particular column in a grid and checking whether that particular column in sorted.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- Create a variable to keep track of the number of columns to be deleted. Let's call it `colsDelete`. 
- Have an outer loop to iterate over the length of any string in `strs`. (Since all the strings in `strs` have same length)
- The inner loop will iterate over all the strings in `strs` i.e. `strs.length`. This ensures that we are traversing columnwise. 
- Now check whether `(strs[j].charAt(i) < strs[j-1].charAt(i))`. This means we are checking whether two adjacent rows in a column are lexiographically sorted or not.
- If not then increment `colsDelete` and `break` the inner loop as we do not need to check further whether that column is sorted.
- Finally, after checking for all columns, return `colsDelete`


# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int minDeletionSize(String[] strs) {
        int colsDelete = 0; 

        //Iterating over the length of any string in strs. Here we took strs[0]
        for(int i=0; i<strs[0].length(); i++){

            //Iterating over all the strings in strs
            for(int j=1; j<strs.length; j++){

                if(strs[j].charAt(i) < strs[j-1].charAt(i)){
                    colsDelete++;
                    break;
                } 
            }
        }
        return colsDelete;
    }
}
```

