# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The first intuition is that we will have to iterate through the entire string vector and compare each char of each string in it.

We will also have to store the status of each column (whether sorted or not) to find out how many total columns do we actually need to delete.

--> We cannot simply make a counter variable and do *counter++* when there is an unsorted occurance because a column may have more than one unsorted occurances and in this case, then result will be incorrect. 
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. If the vector of strings has only one element, then we do not need to delete anything because a single element is always sorted in itself. Hence, directly return 0.
2. Else, create a bool array (sorted here) of size equal to the number of columns such that each index denotes each column status.
3. Initially, initialize each column status as true (means sorted).
4. Iterate through the entire vector of strings from its second element and keep comparing its each char with the char of previous element at the same index.
5. If any unsorted order occurs, change the status of that corresponding column to false (denoting that it needs to be deleted).
6. Finally count all the number of false occurances in the bool array and return that value as the required output.
# Complexity
- Time complexity = $$O(n * len)$$
where, n = length of vector of strings and 
len = length of each string in it or the total number of columns.
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity = $$O(n)$$
for using boolean array to hold the status of each column.
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int minDeletionSize(vector<string>& str) {
        int n = str.size() ;

        if(n == 1) return 0 ;

        int len = str[0].length() ;
        bool sorted[len] ;    //To store result of each column.
        memset(sorted, true, sizeof(sorted)) ;

        for(int i=1; i<n; i++){
            for(int j=0; j<len; j++){
                if(str[i][j] < str[i-1][j]){
                    sorted[j] = false ;
                }
            }
        }

        int count = 0 ;
        for(int i=0; i<len; i++){
            if(!sorted[i]){
                count++ ;
            }
        }

        return count ;
    }
};
```

